  #Spatial Offline Report Crafter
        
##Purpose:
This AI agent template is meant for workflows where the client has some spatial data and needs to ingest multiple files from
    field staff in a semi-unstructured format. Run each phase with
    specific paths to your data. Make sure everything for a phase is
    complete and then proceed with the next phase prompts.
    
    Report generation dependency:
    - HTML DOCX report scripts live in a separate reusable git project:
    https://github.com/GetBack2Basics/Spatial_Offline_Report_Crafter
    - Use this report project after creating the review GPKG to produce
    client-ready outputs.
    - Required review GPKG layers: *_new_review, *_drift_review,
    *_displacement_vector
    - Recommended columns: Asset_ID or asset_id, Drift_m, Risk_Level,
    Review_PotentialChange, Review_Status, Src_CSV, Src_Type, Src_Date,
    Src_Value, Comments
    - Call the report scripts directly from their installed/cloned paths:
      - scripts/build_html_report.py — produces
    Reconciliation_Review.html + map assets
      - scripts/create_extract_docx.py — produces a native DOCX summary extract
    - For HTML script usage details, see scripts/build_html_report.md in
    that same project
    
    GIS DATA WORKFLOW PHASES
    
    PHASE 1: DISCOVER
    - Inspect source folder structure
    - Identify domains and file formats
    - Read sample records, check geometry columns
    - Validate geometry types match expected assets
    (points/lines/polygons)
    - If endpoint access required: probe sample first; if fail, inform
    user and stop before bulk operations
    - Summarize findings: count, formats, geometry status, data quality red flags
    - ASK USER: agree source inventory and domain scope before proceeding
    
    PHASE 2: SCOPE & DESIGN
    - Propose review fields and classification rules with user
    - Define drift threshold, attribute comparison columns, status flags
    - Agree on review GPKG layer names and symbology categories
    - Agree on output paths and target write-back locations
    - Confirm no source/original files will be modified unless
    explicitly requested
    - ASK USER: approve scope before writing any scripts
    
    PHASE 3: PREPARE & VALIDATE
    - Write all scripts needed for the workflow (ingest, clean, match,
    build outputs into review GPKG)
    - STOP and face user review of scripts and paths
    - Do not run pipelines yet
    - Fix small issues flagged by user inline
    - ASK USER: approve script batch before execution
    
    PHASE 4: EXECUTE
    - Run ingestion and cleaning scripts
    - Generate review GPKG with classified features and flags
    - Build reports and maps using the report project scripts against
    the review GPKG
    - If any step returns zero features or unexpected nulls, halt and report
    - ASK USER after each major step: review output counts and samples
    before continuing
    
    PHASE 5: REVIEW & ITERATE
    - Present findings: new assets, drift counts, flagged records,
    displacement vectors using generated HTML and DOCX reports
    - Highlight data quality issues found
    - Make small fixes if user requests
    - Regenerate outputs if logic changed
    - ASK USER: confirm analysis output before write-back or final report
    
    PHASE 6: COMMIT & DOCUMENT
    - Run write-back dry-run and show diff
    - Only after approval: run commit write-back
    - Regenerate final report if needed
    - Document run parameters, counts, thresholds used
    - ASK USER: green light for production ingestion or archive instead
    
    GENERAL RULES (all phases)
    - Use safe field expressions; avoid non-existent functions
    - Match field lengths to source or trim explicitly
    - Never modify files outside designated working directory without permission
    - Probe external endpoints before depending on them
    - Verify geometry column names from actual source; do not assume defaults
    - Keep outputs separate from inputs until user approves write-back
    - Ask only when blocked or decision required; otherwise execute, fix
    small things, then report
    - For HTML reports, keep native folium basemap controls; only
    post-process for metadata links and custom WMS form
    - For DOCX reports, use native document format with structured
    tables and summary sections
